U||CHAPTER VII‚ÄîTHE WISDOM OF THOLOMY√àS
U||In the meantime, while some sang, the rest talked together tumultuously all at once; it was no longer anything but noise. Tholomy√®s intervened.
U||‚ÄúLet us not talk at random nor too fast,‚Äù he exclaimed. ‚ÄúLet us reflect, if we wish to be brilliant. Too much improvisation empties the mind in a stupid way. Running beer gathers no froth. No haste, gentlemen. Let us mingle majesty with the feast. Let us eat with meditation; let us make haste slowly. Let us not hurry. Consider the springtime; if it makes haste, it is done for; that is to say, it gets frozen. Excess of zeal ruins peach-trees and apricot-trees. Excess of zeal kills the grace and the mirth of good dinners. No zeal, gentlemen! Grimod de la Reyni√®re agrees with Talleyrand.‚Äù
