U||Before proceeding further, and in order to make ourselves fully understood, let us insist upon one necessary observation.
U||It is certain that people do talk to themselves; there is no living being who has not done it. It may even be said that the word is never a more magnificent mystery than when it goes from thought to conscience within a man, and when it returns from conscience to thought; it is in this sense only that the words so often employed in this chapter, he said, he exclaimed, must be understood; one speaks to one‚Äôs self, talks to one‚Äôs self, exclaims to one‚Äôs self without breaking the external silence; there is a great tumult; everything about us talks except the mouth. The realities of the soul are nonetheless realities because they are not visible and palpable.
U||So he asked himself where he stood. He interrogated himself upon that ‚Äúsettled resolve.‚Äù He confessed to himself that all that he had just arranged in his mind was monstrous, that ‚Äúto let things take their course, to let the good God do as he liked,‚Äù was simply horrible; to allow this error of fate and of men to be carried out, not to hinder it, to lend himself to it through his silence, to do nothing, in short, was to do everything! that this was hypocritical baseness in the last degree! that it was a base, cowardly, sneaking, abject, hideous crime!
