U||‚ÄúIs it you, Mr. Mayor?‚Äù she exclaimed.
U||He replied in a low voice:‚Äî
U||‚ÄúHow is that poor woman?‚Äù
U||‚ÄúNot so bad just now; but we have been very uneasy.‚Äù
U||She explained to him what had passed: that Fantine had been very ill the day before, and that she was better now, because she thought that the mayor had gone to Montfermeil to get her child. The sister dared not question the mayor; but she perceived plainly from his air that he had not come from there.
U||‚ÄúAll that is good,‚Äù said he; ‚Äúyou were right not to undeceive her.‚Äù
U||‚ÄúYes,‚Äù responded the sister; ‚Äúbut now, Mr. Mayor, she will see you and will not see her child. What shall we say to her?‚Äù
U||He reflected for a moment.
U||‚ÄúGod will inspire us,‚Äù said he.
U||‚ÄúBut we cannot tell a lie,‚Äù murmured the sister, half aloud.
