U||‚ÄúThis signature is fairly well imitated,‚Äù he growled between his teeth; ‚Äúhowever, let it go!‚Äù
U||Then he essayed a desperate effort.
U||‚ÄúIt is well, sir,‚Äù he said, ‚Äúsince you are the person, but I must be paid for all those little things. A great deal is owing to me.‚Äù
U||The man rose to his feet, filliping the dust from his threadbare sleeve:‚Äî
U||‚ÄúMonsieur Th√©nardier, in January last, the mother reckoned that she owed you one hundred and twenty francs. In February, you sent her a bill of five hundred francs; you received three hundred francs at the end of February, and three hundred francs at the beginning of March. Since then nine months have elapsed, at fifteen francs a month, the price agreed upon, which makes one hundred and thirty-five francs. You had received one hundred francs too much; that makes thirty-five still owing you. I have just given you fifteen hundred francs.‚Äù
U||Th√©nardier‚Äôs sensations were those of the wolf at the moment when he feels himself nipped and seized by the steel jaw of the trap.
U||‚ÄúWho is this devil of a man?‚Äù he thought.
