U||On the following day, Ma‚Äôam Bougon, as Courfeyrac styled the old portress-principal-tenant, housekeeper of the Gorbeau hovel, Ma‚Äôam Bougon, whose name was, in reality, Madame Burgon, as we have found out, but this iconoclast, Courfeyrac, respected nothing,‚ÄîMa‚Äôam Bougon observed, with stupefaction, that M. Marius was going out again in his new coat.
U||He went to the Luxembourg again, but he did not proceed further than his bench midway of the alley. He seated himself there, as on the preceding day, surveying from a distance, and clearly making out, the white bonnet, the black dress, and above all, that blue light. He did not stir from it, and only went home when the gates of the Luxembourg closed. He did not see M. Leblanc and his daughter retire. He concluded that they had quitted the garden by the gate on the Rue de l‚ÄôOuest. Later on, several weeks afterwards, when he came to think it over, he could never recall where he had dined that evening.
