U||One evening, little Gavroche had had nothing to eat; he remembered that he had not dined on the preceding day either; this was becoming tiresome. He resolved to make an effort to secure some supper. He strolled out beyond the Salp√™tri√®re into deserted regions; that is where windfalls are to be found; where there is no one, one always finds something. He reached a settlement which appeared to him to be the village of Austerlitz.
U||In one of his preceding lounges he had noticed there an old garden haunted by an old man and an old woman, and in that garden, a passable apple-tree. Beside the apple-tree stood a sort of fruit-house, which was not securely fastened, and where one might contrive to get an apple. One apple is a supper; one apple is life. That which was Adam‚Äôs ruin might prove Gavroche‚Äôs salvation. The garden abutted on a solitary, unpaved lane, bordered with brushwood while awaiting the arrival of houses; the garden was separated from it by a hedge.
U||Gavroche directed his steps towards this garden; he found the lane, he recognized the apple-tree, he verified the fruit-house, he examined the hedge; a hedge means merely one stride. The day was declining, there was not even a cat in the lane, the hour was propitious. Gavroche began the operation of scaling the hedge, then suddenly paused. Some one was talking in the garden. Gavroche peeped through one of the breaks in the hedge.
U||Succor from Below
U||A couple of paces distant, at the foot of the hedge on the other side, exactly at the point where the gap which he was meditating would have been made, there was a sort of recumbent stone which formed a bench, and on this bench was seated the old man of the garden, while the old woman was standing in front of him. The old woman was grumbling. Gavroche, who was not very discreet, listened.
U||‚ÄúMonsieur Mabeuf!‚Äù said the old woman.
U||‚ÄúMabeuf!‚Äù thought Gavroche, ‚Äúthat name is a perfect farce.‚Äù
U||The old man who was thus addressed, did not stir. The old woman repeated:‚Äî
U||‚ÄúMonsieur Mabeuf!‚Äù
U||The old man, without raising his eyes from the ground, made up his mind to answer:‚Äî
U||‚ÄúWhat is it, Mother Plutarque?‚Äù
U||‚ÄúMother Plutarque!‚Äù thought Gavroche, ‚Äúanother farcical name.‚Äù
U||Mother Plutarque began again, and the old man was forced to accept the conversation:‚Äî
U||‚ÄúThe landlord is not pleased.‚Äù
U||‚ÄúWhy?‚Äù
